  <!-- SCANNING PROCEDURE SECTION -->
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-100">
      <h2 id="scanning-procedure" style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font);">7. Scanning & Discovery Procedure</h2>
      
      <h3 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font); font-size: var(--font-size-large);">7.1 Adding a New Device</h3>
      <ol style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font); line-height: 1.8;">
        <li>Check this registry first - Verify which IPs are already in use</li>
        <li>Reserve the IP address - Update this document with the device name and purpose</li>
        <li>Configure the device - Set static IP on the device or reserve in DHCP pool</li>
        <li>Run discovery scan - Verify it responds to ping/nmap</li>
        <li>Update documentation - Add to the appropriate network section</li>
        <li>Test connectivity - Verify from workstation and other servers</li>
      </ol>

      <h3 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font); font-size: var(--font-size-large);">7.2 Running nmap Scans</h3>
      <div style="background-color: var(--light-color); padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
        <pre style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: monospace; margin: 0;"><code>
nmap -sn 192.168.1.0/24          # Quick discovery scan
nmap -p 22,80,443,3306 192.168.1.0/24  # Scan common ports
nmap -v 192.168.1.126            # Detailed scan on specific IP
nmap -sn 192.168.2.0/24          # Scan WiFi network
        </code></pre>
      </div>

      <h3 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font); font-size: var(--font-size-large);">7.3 Using ARP for Discovery</h3>
      <div style="background-color: var(--light-color); padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
        <pre style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: monospace; margin: 0;"><code>
arp -a | sort                    # Display all ARP entries
arp -a | grep 192.168.1          # Filter by network
ping -c 1 192.168.1.X            # Check if IP is in use
nslookup 192.168.1.X             # Hostname resolution
        </code></pre>
      </div>

      <p style="text-align: right; margin-top: var(--spacing-small);"><a href="#toc" style="color: var(--link-color); font-size: var(--font-size-small);">↑ Back to Top</a></p>
    </div>
